Nov 1 2009	Keep it all in perspective	Listen up people! I have travelled around the world &amp; used to be a travel agent. I have stayed in everything from 1 to 5 star hotels, so I know what I'm talking about with this review!My Mom &amp; I recently returned from a truely great one week stay at the Sahara!! This was my second visit there this year. Thats how much I like it!! After reading so many negative reviews we almost re-booked somewhere else, even though I had stayed there just 5 months previous &amp; knew what to expect! After our great stay we can only say that either people are too fussy, or are not well travelled &amp; are expecting too much. Perhaps they are expecting the glitz &amp; glamour that they see on T.V. &amp; in pictures, but with the Sahara you have to keep everything in perspective. Yes, the property is old, the hotel was established in 1952. Unfortunately, because we are in the middle of a recession, we were told by the staff that upgrades that were planned have been put on hold. The common areas are run down, as are some of the rooms, but overall the place is CLEAN!! Yes, there were some room service trays &amp; glasses laying around for awhile in the hallway, but was I going to let something like that ruin my holiday? NO I wasn't! As long as our room &amp; beds were clean thats what mattered. Without fail we found every staff member from the pool boy up to the Asst. Hotel Manager to be very helpful &amp; friendly. Some reviews on this site said the opposite, but we expect those people went in with a negative attitude right from the start, so nothing would have satisfied them. Remember that as with everything in life you get back what you give out. This property is more off the &quot;beaten track&quot;, but my mother who is a senior especailly enjoyed this, as it is a nice retreat when you've had enough of the hustle &amp; bustle of the main strip &amp; since the hotel is smaller its much easier to get around. For those of you who enjoy relaxing in the sun the pool is really nice, but very cold! The dinner buffet for $8.99 with the Sahara Club card discount was adequate. Nothing fancy, but again keep it in perspective when you're paying $8.99 for dinner! You can barely eat at a fast food restaurant for that price!Here are a few tips to make your stay here more enjoyable:1.) Try and check in on a Sunday or Monday if possible. There are virtually no line ups to check in on those days. 2.) Ask for a more recently renovated room in the Tangiers Tower, preferrably high up from the 25th - 27th floors. DO NOT book a standard room. Pay a little more &amp; get a deluxe or premium room. Some people seem to have had bad experiences with dirty rooms and we suspect they are the ones that stayed in a standard room low down.3.) This hotel is conveniently located on the Monorail line. Pay a little more &amp; buy the 3 day unlimited rides monorail pass, $30.00. Its worth the money!! You can get from one end of the strip to the other in about 20 minutes. It beats all the stops on a crowded bus on the strip!We looking forward to going back!	
