Sep 14 2009	What a Dump!	A large group of family and friends had gathered for my niece's 21st birthday, and since I knew I would be doing some entertaining, I had reserved a suite. My sister-in-law had selected the hotel because of the low rates (I would never have chosen this place). Just driving up to the place was evidence of the rundown area which was to be our stomping ground for the next 3 days. A cab ride to the better part of the strip will cost you about $20 - be prepared. Youl could take the tram, but you're looking at $15 round-trip there, as well. After waiting in line almost an hour to check in, we were given the keys to our suite. On the way, we passed the loung area next to the check-in area, and I was appalled to see a huge sectional that was so filtthy and run down, it looked as though someone had found it abandoned on the street and had brought it back to the hotel (not a good omen). Anyway, on to the room.... Upon first sight, the suite was large, with ample seating. However, the initial impression was immediately replaced with the reality: the room was over 80 degrees (with the air on full-blast), the telephone did not work, 2 of the lamps in the room did not work, the refrigerator in the bar did not work, the carpet was stained and filthy, and 3 of the pieces of furniture were torn and/or broken. I had to use my cell phone to call the front desk to report the non-functioning room phone, and was told an assistant manager would bring up a new one. After waiting almost another hour (in the hot room), a surly assistant manager showed up with a new phone (which also did not work), and made it very clear that he had no interest whatsoever in hearing about the list of unacceptable items in the room. He made some remark about the problems being technical in nature, and disappeared to &quot;see what he could do.&quot; There was never an &quot;I'm sorry&quot; for the inconvenience, or even the slightest hint that he gave one damn at all. Forty minutes later, a bellman showed up to move us to a different suite. We were taken to a different room in a different tower, and while the room was cleaner and in better condition that the last, the suite was quite a bit smaller. The asst. mgr. said it was the only suite available, a statement I later discovered was a bold-face lie. In the end, I had guests over to a much smaller room, some of whom actually had to sit on the carpeting. I should have been given a comparable room, or been upgraded. Instead, I was given less than I had reserved over a month before. My overall impression of the Sahara is that it is rundown, dirty, falling apart, and run by people who just don't give a damn. Hell will freeze over before I ever stay at this dump again!	
