Sep 4 2009 	The secret to a great time at the Sahara- and it won't cost much	The Sahara has many advantages. The weak link is the room selection so always ask to upgrade to the rooms in the Tangiers tower floors 25-27 and make sure your room has a flat screen so you know it is a newly remodeled room. The buffet is good but average so I'd eat there with a free buffet comp only and choose the Nascar cafe, Cravan cafe or Pacos if your paying.The reason I choose this casino is they have great food at the restaurants, good comps (even minimal gambling can earn free food, drinks or slot play) the pool is clean and big and rarely full, you can get the monorail right in the hotel, the shows are great (I saw the Platters, Coasters and was really impressed), free slot tournaments and prices were reasonable. For people on a budget there are $1.00 beer specials and $1.00 hot dogs as well as $1.00 Blackjack.Yes you can stay at a more modern and updated casino but then will you be able to afford to eat or drink there? My sister got great room prices at Mandalay Bay and had to walk to another hotel every day for breakfast because of prices.One last comment - the Sahara is a quick cab ride to downtown and right across from the Stratoshpere.	
Aug 30 2009 	Enjoyable overnight at the Sahara	I ended up at the Sahara at the last minute, upon discovering Excalibur booked up on a Sunday evening, and was pleasantly surprised by the overall value of the place. Bear in mind, my only requirements for a place on that particular evening was that it be somewhere on the Strip, relatively cheap, and close to a monorail station. The Sahara definitely exceeded my expectations for $35-40/night room. The location isn't great, but if you like the Strip hotels, the monorail station is right there to take you wherever you want to go. Time has caught up with the place a bit, and an overhaul wouldn't be the worst thing, but there is a lot of charm to the Sahara's old-Vegas feel. Most importantly, it was clean and I found the staff to be among the friendliest that I've experienced in Las Vegas, and infinitely more pleasant than their contemporaries in other gaming markets (Connecticut, Atlantic City, etc.).	
