May 7 2009 	SAHARA!	I attended the SEMA show at the Las Vegas convention center about two and a half years ago with my father and we stayed here for two nights. This was my second trip to Las Vegas and one of my first experiences with a Vegas style hotel (my first visit was only a day trip). Initially, my father had booked us for the whole trip at the &quot;Tropicana&quot; but after realizing how far it was from the convention center we checked into here after one night.First off, I have to say that this has got to be one of your best choices if you're concerned about proximity to the convention center. It's pretty close and has it's own monorail stop that can get you there or anywhere else on the strip. I believe they do have updated rooms (though from the pictures I've seen they are unimpressive) but ours was a standard and had two queen beds. The decor and furnishings of the room were definitely a little outdated. The beds were the same that you'd probably find in an economy hotel anywhere else and the room was also equipped with a 19&quot; tube television with limited channels. Our view consisted mainly of a parking lot and the monorail station but we could also make out the &quot;Stratosphere&quot; in the distance. I'd imagine if you book there lowest rate on a travel site they would put you in one of these rooms.We tried a couple of their restaurants during our stay with the first being the &quot;NASCAR Cafe&quot;. I'd compare this to an &quot;Applebees&quot; or &quot;T.G.I. Fridays&quot;. Typical sports bar atmosphere and food. If you're a fan of &quot;NASCAR&quot; you may be impressed by all of the memorabilia and the full sized race car replica hanging from the ceiling. It really was okay and I've been back on another trip (though did not stay at the hotel, that time.) We also ate at &quot;Paco's Bar and Grill&quot; which I believe is only open for dinner. This restaurant is located off the casino floor in a much nicer room than the &quot;NASCAR Cafe&quot;. There really wasn't anything special or out of the ordinary here... it was pretty much a Mexican style sports bar. I'd compare it to &quot;Chevy's&quot; or &quot;Garcias&quot;. Going back to something I mentioned earlier... the &quot;Sahara&quot;, much like other lower level hotels on the strip, offers only very limited cable channels. We didn't even get ESPN and were looking forward to catching the first game of our teams 06/07 NBA season. We decided to watch the game in their tiny sports book, which wasn't a problem at first as it was mostly deserted and had comfortable chairs. About halfway through the game the guy managing the sports book told us he had to change all of the TV's to a particular channel according to their policy. Apparently they do it every weeknight around 10 PM or so. It seemed a little ridiculous, considering my father and I were the only ones even in the sports book at this point... but we went back to &quot;Paco's Bar and Grill&quot; and finished the game in there. To be honest, I'd probably rate this hotel as being at least as nice as it's direct competitors (Circus Circus, Riviera, etc) but it's just too far. If you stay here, you should really plan on a lot of walking... and even then, you're in for a real hike if you want to go any further than the &quot;Riviera&quot;. Those standard rooms do go for super cheap, though, so don't be too afraid to book it if you find a good deal. I'd suggest you utilize either the monorail or the Deuce bus if you stay here.	
May 5 2009 	Good quality and great value	This is a fairly old hotel by Vegas standards, and is a little lost on one end of the 'Strip', being about 10 minutes walk from the centre (NB this is not the centre of the city, that is somewhere a little more distant, a place known as 'downtown'). Alternatively the monorail stops right outside. The rooms are a little worn, but large, clean and comfortable. There are shops within about 5 minutes where you can get basic provisions (including my favourite US shop Walgreens where you can get everything). There are coffee shops and various eatieries in the casino, but I didn't try them. The service at the front desk checking in can be a bit slow, but you can check out in the room, so that is quick. I would recommend this hotel, although not if you are desperate to be right in the centre of the action.	
May 2 2009 	Subdued Nostalgia on a Dime	This stay was my and my husband's second time at the Sahara. It's one of the last old-school hotels in Vegas - the rooms do require touch-ups, but if you're looking for a clean room, good gaming and friendly service at an excellent price, then you'll appreciate it here. Management should replace the televisions in the rooms, and the mattress could have stood to be more firm for our preferences. The dinner buffet is economical, but it's certainly not great quality fare - better to head out to the multitude of fabulous restaurants in the city. Excellent location from which to explore the South Strip, Fremont Street, and the Fashion Outlet Malls with the Monorail and the Deuce at the doorsteps. Caravan Cafe offers a good breakfast menu in a 60s diner atmosphere. Wait staff were professional and friendly. My husband and I would certainly stay here again. After the lights and action of Vegas, it's relaxing to come back to a subdued atmosphere - and one that allows us to come in well under budget.	
