Apr 24 2009 	A great budget hotel on the strip	We stayed at the Sahara after finding a great last minute flight and hotel deal on expedia.co.uk. I’ve been to Vegas before so knew about the location being slightly seedier down that end of the strip. I must admit a couple of times walking to and from the Deuce bus stop I felt a little uneasy, especially after dark, because it’s very quiet that end of the strip and we were asked for change a couple times. We had absolutely no complaints with our hotel room, it was very old and had a few stains but nothing that bothered us, and we were so tired at the end of the day anyway! One thing we absolutely hated was the pool. They had a terrible sound system and played very loud, banging music constantly which meant you couldn’t relax or read a book because the bass just gave you a headache. If it hadn’t been for the music the pool would have been fine, a nice place to unwind and soak up the sun. We didn’t do any gambling so I can’t comment on that, but we did try the buffet, which was great. Cheap and lots of choice and it all tasted lovely. It was also great having a coffee shop at the bottom of the elevators to get our breakfast from, and an off licence to get beers for the room. If you’re on a budget and want a hotel on the strip I wouldn’t discourage staying here, it’s so easy to hop on the Deuce (every 10 mins and $15 for a 3 day pass) to get to the main action.	
Apr 23 2009 	Good hotel cheap rates but needs a refit	This hotel is not as bad as other reviews here make it out to be. Sure, if you're looking for a new casino with all the bells and whistles, this is not the place for you - it is an old set of buildings and it shows. However, I was here for a conference and as a hotel it was pretty suitable.Check-in was quick and easy, but then again I checked in during the late evening - in the afternoons I saw very long lines of people waiting to check in, and very few attendants to check them in. The room was good - I stayed in the Tunis Tower on the 25th floor, and had an ok view towards the Wynn and the Circus Circus. The room was large and clean, the beds were comfortable and well-made, and the bathroom was clean and well-equipped. The room service personnel were friendly and very helpful - they even asked me on several days at what time I would like my room cleaned, and they actually showed up at the agreed times.The interior of the casino is, however, lacking; the place could have done with more stores selling food and drinks - instead, you get a well-equipped liquor store where water is extremely expensive. The sit-down cafe diner could have done with lower prices and a more attractive decor - dark brown is just not on. The casino floor staff, especially some of the barmen on the main floor, seemed to treat customers as though they were annoyances rather than paying customers...all they seemed to be waiting for was the tip.The internet was expensive and there was only a pay-per-day option, no pay-per-week option available. And I did not like the 'compulsory' daily facilities charge which the hotel adds to your bill at the end of your stay - this is supposed to cover the use of facilities such as the pool, but I was there in March, so the pool was never used because it was too cold outside. Furthermore, the facilities were not well-maintained - the ice machine on my floor was broken all week, and the drinks vending machine ate my money!	
Apr 14 2009 	You aren't affriad to sit on the bed but you awake ready to get out of the room	My husband and I stayed at the Sahara located on the far end of the strip at the beginning of April. We won the stay and so I probably was less dissastified because it didnt cost me anything to stay there.we actually stayed in the most recently constructed part of the hotel and while I wasn&quot;t affraid to sleep in the bedsheets, you awoke every morning eager to leave the drab hotel rrom and smokey casino lobby. Okay you expect smoke in casino's but the Sahara is by far one of the more smokey facilities....due in part to the hotel being older and the ceiling being low and ventilation system being antiquated. All that being said, the hotel was suitable, not bad, not good...it has a few restaurants, an all night cafe (its worth the $$$ to wait til 1am to eat as the twilight specials are half the menu price) a casino and bar with shows etc. It was okay. I could appreciate the security guard positioned outside the elevators to go upstairs...(although he did not check for room keys the entire time I was there, but the appearance of safety was better than nothing)The valet was speedy, the self parking was quick and easy, the bell service was efficient, and there is a rail station at the hotel (you will not want to walk to the central stip from this hotel) but this hotel is a glimpse of borderline &quot;seedy&quot; Vegas... you will not be wowed by much, but you wont get bed bugs either. If you are on a budget I would recommend, if you can afford better then upgrade to another hotel.One regret...I did not get to ride the roller coaster.	
