Mar 30 2009 	Not Worth It	My fiancé and I stayed at the Sahara over the weekend for a wedding. It seemed to be the best deal on the strip at $90/night for a &quot;premium&quot; room. But I guess that should have raised a red flag.When we first got in the room, it seemed decent. It was quite warn, smelt old, and looked like it needed a remodel. It was also really hot on the entire floor. But I had seen worse. It was a non-smoking room with a king bed, just as we had requested. Seemed good enough.The next day, as we dressed for the wedding, I caught a cockroach running across the floor. Not acceptable. Even though it was a single bug, you know that's not the kind that travels alone. Not in a place like that.On our way to the wedding, we stopped at the front-desk to complain. The clerk gave us a bit of attitude, though she said they would switch our room. We told her we had a wedding to get to, so she said to just come back and they would switch us. Okay...Came back exhausted to change clothes, so we thought we would just call the front-desk to speed along the process, since there was a huge line forming there now. Should have been easy, but we could barely get anyone on the phone! Either we got a busy signal, or it just rang and rang. After 10 minutes, my finace called the bellhop. They answered immediately, and even told us just to skip the line and go straight to a window at the desk to request the new room.After finally getting the keys for the new room, we called the bellhop back, and he came in less than 5 minutes to move us. Though when we entered room #2, we realized that it was not a premium room, and that it also had two full sized beds, instead of a king. This room was also extremely warn, much worse than the first one.We attempted to call the desk, but realized that would not get us anywhere again. It just rang this time, so I assumed they were ignoring us at this point. Down we went to the desk.We explained our issues all over again. The only thing the clerk responded with was, &quot;Oh, that wasn't a roach, that was just a water bug... we have those here!&quot; That remark made me quite livid, though luckily my fiancé quickly said, &quot;Look, we just need you guys to make this right.&quot; Out came the manager.Once again, we explained our issues. He managed to at least look concerned and upset about the situation, though he made excuses about the number of available rooms. My fiancé said again that he just wanted it made right somehow. So the manager claimed he understood, and then disappeared into the back room for about 5 minutes. He came back saying he would reduce our rate down to $35/night, and that he was looking for another room for us. 10 minutes after that, they apparently found one.Room number 3 was similar to our first one, but not quite as nice. Though at this point, we were done playing musical rooms. It was apparent that at the Sahara, you weren't going to get any better.Overall, both the cleanliness and the customer service needs a complete overhaul. The place looks and smells dingy. There was spilt ice cream in the hall at one point, and it took at least a day before the packaging for it was even picked up (it was still melted into the carpet). I assume their care for the rooms must be the same. And the fact that most of the staff just shrugs away complaints, or even argues with you about them is extremely frustrating. I worked in customer service for 5 years... you just don't respond that way!I appreciate that the manager did attempt to make it right for all of our troubles, but in the end, it was not worth it. I would much rather pay a bit more elsewhere and not have to deal with such a disgusting atmosphere. I can't see this place surviving much longer, especially considering all of the negative reviews that sound similar to this one.	
