May 28 2008 	Decent value if saving money is a priority	Over the years we have stayed at the Sahara in the past, I had always thought it was a fairly nice hotel for the price and after trying a few of the other hotels on my more recent trips we decided to return to the Sahara.Overall the Sahara is not a bad choice for the younger crowd. I noticed on many of my trips to this hotel that there are many people in the 25-40 range staying here which we really liked. But for those who like having close access to the other attractions on the Las Vegas strip, the Sahara is not the wisest choice. Unless you are in great shape and the weather is good the walk to the middle of the strip is quite a long one. The Sahara is pretty much sharing the end of the strip with the Stratosphere and as of the date of this review, the next closest hotel is about a block away.As for the rooms, this is where I found the major difference from my previous stays. We were given a room in the Alexandria tower which was a first for us. We had always had rooms in the Tangiers tower on previous stays. Our room which was on the 4th floor seemed very old and out of date. The wall paper was hideous and the carpets and tile in the room and bathroom were so worn and stained. The beds were in okay shape; these were probably the only things in the room that didn't look as if a million people have come through them. Overall these rooms definitely need a makeover. Although I wouldn't classify the room as bad, it was far from the pleasant memory I had of my previous stays at the Sahara. A person in our group had a room in the Tangiers tower to which we paid a visit and per my recollections, the room was indeed in much better shape than our room in the Alexandria tower. I think the Tangiers tower is newer and therefore a bit more modernized. They have another tower called the Tunis tower which is where my sister-in-laws stayed that I didn't get to see but according to my sister, their room was worse than ours. The Alexandria and Tunis towers are located closer to the casino and the Tangiers tower is located at the rear of the hotel. Although the Tangiers tower is a longer walk to get to, I think I will ask for a room in that tower now that I've seen the differences in the room quality.Also, we noticed that the rooms vary quite a bit. In the Alexandria tower we had room 430 which was very small and basic. Friends of ours in the same tower had room 2023 which was a corner room and very spacious. They also had a separate wash basin and cabinet area in their room. Others in our group got a room in the same tower but because theirs was a smoking room, they had a balcony. Our room in 430 didn't have a balcony or a view so it was very basic.The only problem our friends had in room 2023 was that they said it took forever to catch the elevator from their floor. We never had that issue but then again we were only on the fourth floor.The hotel's casino is pretty good. Plenty of variety for game playing. The buffet at this hotel has been one of my favorites. We went for brunch and were very pleased with the variety. On our last day we had the buffet brunch at the Excalibur and were somewhat disappointed with the variety there as opposed to the Sahara which ranged from breakfast to asian to mexican and beyond. Nothing fancy but definitely satisfying for hungry tummies.One of the better features at this hotel is the pool scene. There are plenty of chairs for lounging around their large pool and they have a bar and music playing. Lots of pretty people were lounging by the pool and hanging out just relaxing and enjoying the warm sun. On Sunday we even noticed as we were leaving that they were barbequing and had food out. Lastly the parking garages had plenty of parking despite being a holiday weekend (Memorial Day) but they have some of the oldest, creakiest elevators I've ever been in. They definitely need to be upgraded in the near future.Overall, the Sahara is still a decent deal and given my Vegas needs in the future it will definitely be considered again. Just go knowing what Sahara has to offer; if it doesn't suit your expectations for accessibility to other hotels on the strip or more upscale rooms, you might want to consider another hotel. But if you're like me and prefer to save your Vegas money for fun rather than a room, the Sahara is a great choice and can provide many other perks to compensate.	
May 26 2008	Ick Ick and Ick	Hotel was booked through Priceline. You basically get what you paid for. Very old hotel and the rooms have paper thin walls. I could hear everything that was going on in the room next door, and I am not a light sleeper. The pool area was nice, we did not go swimming as it was February, but it was nice enough to sit outside to catch some rays.The Buffet, let's just say was less than appetizing. I can't think of anything good that I had, other than the saltine crackers. The alfredo sauce was old and smelled really bad. Hotel is located on the upper North part of Las Vegas Blvd, up by the Stratosphere. We took the Monorail, which has a station at the hotel, so we wouldn't have to deal with the traffic along the strip. This was nice, however it is $5 for a one way trip. To me that is a little steep. We ended up driving after that.	
May 26 2008 	Great Stay for first time in Vegas	My family and I stayed here for 4 nights in June 2005.Check in was quick and easy. We had two rooms booked which were connected. Rooms were big and spacious, two Double beds in each, Large bathroom, The view from the window was facing away from the Strip but still good enough. The Casino was good, The Resturant choice is great. The NAS QCar cafe was great fun, The Buffet was great for the price. The Pool area was big and clean. The roller coaster was short but fun. Only downside really was the location, Its on the north or the strip, Bit away from the other big hotels. But its on the Monorail so getting to the other hotels on the strip was easy. On my Vist back to Vegas in 07 I re visted the Sahara Its still like it was in 05, The food in the NASQ cafe has got better I think.	
May 23 2008	Good enough	I read a bunch of reviews for this place and wasn't terribly excited. If I had been booking far in advance or during the off-peak season, I would have looked elsewhere. However, I happened to be looking for a room during some shopping center conference and rooms were expensive all along the strip! The only places on the strip were the Imperial Palace ($152), the Stratosphere ($102), and the Sahara ($49). After reading about the IP and learning the Sahara was directly on the monorail, I booked with the Sahara - and I'm glad I did. The Sahara is an old joint with a ton of history. Unfortunately, that doesn't do you a lot of good when you're just looking to drink, gamble, and have fun. The Sahara is pretty dated and could use an overhaul, but it's got everything you really need - a big casino, some crappy food, a nice pool area, and plenty of cheap rooms. All in all I think it was a good choice for the money. Depending on when you go you might be able to get a better place for the money. But if you can't, it's not terribly inconvenient since the monorail station is almost literally in the hotel. Check-in time was absurd, but the line is right next to the convenience store (which has plenty of beer). And don't buy beer at the pool bar - buy a Foster's can at the convenience store for half of what their asking outside and sneak it outside. Of course it'll get real warm real fast, but that's the desert for you...	
