May 3 2008 	The Sahara a Classic	The Sahara is apparently one of the last remaining classic hotels of the early days of Vegas. They were celebrating their 55th Anniversary, which for Vegas, is old! The hotel has been somewhat renovated. The outside was lovely. The pool area, though smaller than some of the other hotels on the strip, was of ample size, accomodating and pretty. The rooms on the other hand are in dire need of renovation. While it was clean, it had an old, musty smell to it, the carpet was worn, the mattress was extremely uncomfortable, the bathroom was old, and the tub faucet dripped.As this was my third stay in Las Vegas, the most noticeable difference, aside from aesthics, was service. In some of the other newer hotels, for example, when you arrive from the airport with your bags, there's someone there to assist with them - not here. When you sit by the pool, a server would come by asking you if you are in need of a drink - not here. When you needed a cab, there was someone there to hail you one - not here. I'm sure if I asked I would have received, but in a way, it wasn't as invasive as the other places - and certainly saved us money on tips.We only ate in the cafe and the coffee bar. The cafe was good - like diner service. The coffee bar had great coffee, and offered muffins, cake, bagels and sandwiches - which were ok.The hotel does have direct access to the monorail system, which is extremely convenient and fast.We did not have any problems or delays checking in or out. But let me say, we checked in on a Tuesday and out on Friday. In the end, the stay was quite pleasant - not as luxurious as some of the other hotels, but for the price, more than acceptable.	
