Apr 30 2008 	Worthwhile option	I travel to Las Vegas every year for a convention. The convention is held in the Las Vegas Convention Center (LVCC). I have stayed at the LV Hilton the past 5 years, but with hotel room rates climbing, I decided to try something less expensive but still hopefully as convenient as the Hilton, which is right next to the LVCC. During the convention, the Sahara was almost half the rate as the Hilton. I booked the room through the convention hotel reservation system.Convenience to and from the LVCC is a primary concern for me on these trips. I chose the Sahara because it has a Monorail stop, so I knew I could get to and from the LVCC quickly. This was also convenient in the evening to get to events on the Strip. The walk from the Sahara Monorail stop to my room in the Sahara was not really that much farther than the walk to the back of the Hilton from the Hilton Monorail stop, so except for the rail time and ticket, I was breaking even. This small sacrifice was well worth it in the end.The Sahara itself offered a pleasant stay. My room was clean, quiet and secure, which are my primary concerns in a hotel. The room had some signs of wear, but nothing drastic or unacceptable. There was an odd stain on the seat of the desk chair, but with two side chairs, I had other seating options.My interaction with the hotel staff was limited to check-in and check-out. Both experiences were pleasant. The hotel offers Internet access in the room. I had a problem connecting at first, and when I called the desk about it, an engineer was sent to my room within 10 minutes to investigate the problem, which turned out to be a faulty cable. I also had some trouble uploading files to an FTP during (working during a convention), but the problem was not significant. (Files would upload, but there was no confirmation that the file transfer was complete without closing the FTP browser and relaunching it. I figured this out quickly enough and made due.) This is not a common Internet use at a hotel, and access to other site and e-mail was trouble-free.Because I was there for a convention, I did not eat at the hotel restaurants this time, but the available choices looked good. I'll try them next time.For my needs on this trip, the Sahara was an ideal choice. If I were visiting Vegas for a gambling excursion, there are plenty of other choices available, although the rate at the Sahara was attractive. If the room-rate comparison is in my favor, I will more than likely stay at the Sahara for the convention again next year.	
