Apr 23 2008 	Sahara Adventure	We arrived in Vegas after travelling from Memphis. We were late due to delays and tired. The hotel staff at check in were very friendly and efficient. We stayed in the North Tower with a view of the escalator to the monorail station. However, all we wanted was somewhere clean and comfortable to sleep and this was great. The room was plenty big enough, very clean and we were very impressed with housekeeping. Location is a bit dismal. Although it's on the monorail line, it's quite a long journey to get to the actual station. It involves possibly the worlds longest escalator ( which broke down and we had to walk up - not fun at all) and a very cold and windy walk across the bridge to cross the street. We ate in the Caravan Cafe which was fabulous. Great service and great food. Also ate in the Nascar Cafe which was dismal. Service was appalling and the food was mediocre at best. The Sahara is very hit and miss. Great at some things and awful at others.	
Apr 21 2008 	Not as bad as I'd read here	In Vegas for a convention and looking for a lower-priced property. -- the Sahara was it.The hotel is certainly on the older, scruffy end of things in this &quot;new&quot; city but hardly the bedbug-ridden hostelry others have written of. The room I had in the Tangiers Tower on the 11th floor was non-smoking, spacious and clean. The hallways and casino area will never smell like anything other than stale smoke, though.The pool area was great but.... 1) it closes at 6pm, 2) The noise from the adjacent roller-coaster ride is horribly irritating.The Sahara is a long hike from downtown. The Deuce double-decker bus seemed like a good idea but only do it once to get the lay of the land. The thing takes nearly an hour to get from the north end of the Strip to the south end. It stops along the way (for 7 minutes at one stop!) to maintain it's &quot;schedule&quot; -- really irritating. The traffic along the Strip makes the bus ride long but even more tedious is the amount of time it takes to load new passengers on. Each person has to feed the toll machine $2.The monorail is a fast way to travel downtown from the Sahara. It isn't cheap and it's also quite a long walk to and from the tracks for those who may have difficulty walking.Overall I'd recommend the Sahara to people who don't mind walking a lot and who are looking to spend their money on things other than the room they sleep in.	
