Apr 15 2008 	It was OK but ....	I quite liked the Sahara. Sure it's an older hotel and it's a little frayed around the edges but it offered good value for money. The room was clean and fairly spacious. The price was right and the $6.99 dinner buffet is a deal. While it is obviously not a glitzy as some of the newer higher priced hotels on the strip it does have a certain old Vegas charm which I enjoy. As it is located at the Northern end of the strip it can be quite a walk if you want to explore other hotels and casinos. And good luck trying to get on the constantly packed to capacity bus that runs up down the strip. We stood at the bus stop and watched bus after bus go by before giving up on the idea.For a few bucks extra the monorail is a much better alternative to taking the bus.Now for the gripes: Check-in and check-out was slow. They really need more people on the check-in/out desk.It might be common practice in Vegas, I'm not sure, but the fact that they ding you an extra $6 a day Facilities Fee instead of just including it in the cost of the hotel was a little annoying to me.Also, we booked the room through Hotwire and I assume because of this the hotel would not accept our request for a non-smoking room or bed type preference when we contacted them directly. Luckily a non-smoking room was available when we checked in which was fortunate as my wife has asthma/allergies and if we had not been able to get a non-smoking room we would have had to find a room elsewhere. I think this is an unacceptable practice in this day and age.Overall, we enjoyed our stay at the Sahara and would certainly stay there again if we could be guaranteed a non-smoking room prior to arrival.	
