Mar 29 2008 	Loved the Classic Vegas Experience	The Sahara has a sense of classic Vegas history, and it's the best deal on the Strip. The casino itself is cozy with a lot of gambling options. Service was consistently courteous not only in the casino, but also in the shops, restaurants, and hotel. There's a broad range of restaurants on the premises. Dinner buffet was mediocre, but it was more than suitable for $6.99. The Caravan Cafe serves a great breakfast. Can also hop on the Monorail to have a meal at the Bellagio (a buffet must), or any other of the mulititude of restaurants on the Strip. An all-day pass can be had for $9, and the entrance to the rail is readily accessible from the casino floor. Expedia included 2-for-1 show tickets that can be used for any performance at the hotel's venues. Trent Carlini's Elvis impersonation was awesome (he won the &quot;Next Best Thing&quot; and is lauded by those who were close to the King). By simply walking out the doors of the hotel and crossing a street, it took one short bus ride (all-day pass for the Deuce is $5) to get to the Fremont Street Experience or the Premium Outlet Mall (fabulous prices for brand name apparel). The hotel room was a bare-boned but clean - it required some touch-ups since the lampshades were a little weathered, and the bathroom counter had a couple of stains. Also, the television was tiny. Since there was a minimal amount of time spent in the room except to sleep, it was fine. Evidently, the Sahara acquired new ownership, and some exciting things are in the works for renovations. Pool area was well-maintained and busy. Sahara appeared to attract a broad range of clientele from conscientious budget travelers to young hipsters and mid-aged folks who shared an appreciation for old school charm. Overall, the stay at the hotel was a pleasant and an enjoyable experience!	
