Feb 2 2008 	You get what you pay for at the Sahara!	I chose the Sahara for this work/fun trip for a couple reasons. The main reason was price. Close behind was proximity to the Las Vegas Convention Center where work was taking me during the day. I also liked the fact the hotel is on the monorail line. Finally, I've been wanting to stay there. I've made a handful of trips to the Sahara on recent &quot;for fun&quot; LV visits to take advantage of their low-limit gambling. An early landing got me to the hotel well before check-in at about 9 AM Las Vegas time. I thought I'd try to see if a room was available or, at the very least, get checked in and have my room assigned later (other LV hotels have done this for me in the past). When I reached the check-in desk, the clerk simply turned me away and told me to check my bags and come back at 3 PM. Mostly I was put off by his attitude toward me, reacting like I was making the most unreasonable request possible. It was the first of many examples of poor service I got at this hotel.The next three days continued the trend. My in-room Internet connection wasn't working. I followed the on-screen instructions on my laptop and called the front desk. My first call wasn't answered after ringing a couple dozen times. When I finally got through, the operator did everything in her power to make me believe the problem was my fault. I finally convinced her the Internet service wasn't turned on in my room. She finally sighed &quot;try it now&quot; and hung up. It indeed worked...after she found her error. I had to follow this process again the next day after my 24 hours were up on the first connection. Being a business traveler, an Internet connection in my room is a necessity. I hate feeling like I have to beg for it.Other annoyances added up. Slow service in their nearly empty cafe at 10 AM. Room key cards that stopped working for no reason. Poor quality buffet. The big and little issues added up to prove that the Sahara does not hold a candle to their neighbors as far as service is concerned.The rooms were interstate motel quality, which was what I expected. Considering I was paying 1/3 - 1/4 of what I'd pay at other properties, I was fine with that quality. I just can't stand when the staff and other amenities live down to the room quality.I won't be returning to the Sarah for business. Oddly, I would recommend it to travelers who simply want a cheap room with a bed and shower to serve as base of operations while they explore the rest of the Strip. The monorail lets you get away to better properties without paying a lot in transport costs. Otherwise, pay a little extra and stay at Ballys, Flamingo, Excalibur or other budget properties.	
