Dec 31 2007 	Good Value Old Vegas Style	The Sahara is 50 years old and shows it; nonetheless it represents one of the cheapest ways to actually stay on the the Las Vegas strip, and one of the last remaining bastions of that &quot;Old Vegas&quot; style.The hotel's new ownership claims that all rooms have been recently renovated, and our room in the Tangiers tower did indeed sport new wallpaper, carpeting, and paint. In addition, the linens appeared new and of a better quality than noted on previous stays.On the negative side, the furniture has not been replaced and is definitely showing its age. Elev ators are slow and sometimes broken. Amazingly, there was no line at all when we checked in on a Friday at 3:00 pm. Subsequent observations indicated that we had caught a lucky break, as lines were normally quite long.We experienced no problems on our stay - service from front desk, parking valets, players club and bell staff was above average to excellent. We enjoyed excellent steaks and outstanding service at the House of Lords, not to mention plenty of the aforementioned &quot;Old Vegas&quot; ambience. However, the Caravan Coffee Shop left much to be desired, with food that could charitably be described as mediocre at best. The best thing that can be said about the buffet is that it is really cheap. Paco's features adequate, albeit Americanized Mexican fare. We did not eat at the Nascar Cafe.While the Sahara will never be mistaken for one of the newer megaresorts, it represents an excellent value for someone looking for old Vegas ambience who would rather save his/her money for the tables.	
