Dec 15 2007 	Superb Sahara	My first visit to Vegas and I stayed at the Sahara November 28th to December 5th. We stayed in a room on floor 24 of the Tangiers Tower. It was a beautiful room, clean, spacious, fantastic views of The Strip and a great size En Suite. We found all members of staff friendly and welcoming. A little old-fashioned but this added to the hotel's atmosphere. Casino was great and we ate lunch in the Caravan Cafe which was cheap and the food was delicious. The monorail stop at the Sahara meant we were literally minutes away from anywhere on The Strip. I would happily stay at The Sahara again. And as for Vegas - WOW.	
Dec 14 2007 	Sahara: A tale of two visits.	Just got back from a trip to Vegas and Arizona and stayed 3 nights at the Sahara - 2 at the beginning of the trip and one near the end. The two experiences couldn't have been more different.When we checked in for the first time we were delighted by the friendliness of the staff and pleased to receive an automatic upgrade to the Tangiers tower.The room was a pretty good size, clean and comfortable with a decent en-suite. Extras included a pretty good hairdryer an iron and ironing board. On the whole we were pretty pleased - particularly given the ridiculously low price we had paid.A week later, we returned from our tour of Az for one additional night prior to moving on to Harrahs. Oh what a different experience. The check-in staff was rude, ill informed and almost deliberately unhelpful. We had booked a non-smoking King some weeks previously but discovered that none was available. The first desk clerk we dealt with was under the (mistaken) impression that we had booked our room through an outside agency and left us in no doubt that we were at the bottom of the food chain as a result. When we pointed out that we'd actually booked direct with the Sahara we were grudgingly given a twin in the Tangiers for an additional fee. The room proved to be just about ok but the 'queen sized' beds were the smallest we've ever experienced and we spent a very 'snug' night as a result. A visit to the casino after check-in revealed dealers &amp; bartenders in a similar mood to the desk clerks. We certainly weren't sorry to check out the following day.The reason for the difference in welcomes was pretty clear, the first time the hotel was half empty and the second time the rodeo was in town and they'd filled up. Quite simply, the Sahara failed the most basic of tests, consistency of service. It's easy to be friendly and professional when you have a handful of guests, a good hotel delivers good service no matter what its occupancy levels.Patchy service aside...the Sahara remains a pretty good budget option. The monorail link and the 'the deuce' have solved its isolation problem. Table limits are lower than other strip casinos and -as one of the oldest remaining relics of old Vegas - the place has a certain shabby chic.The other thing worth mentioning is dining in the hotel. DON'T. We tried the cafe and the breakfast buffet and both were dismal.The bottom line is that you're taking a chance when you choose the Sahara; you could either strike it lucky or strike out. But then that's Vegas all over, right?	
