Oct 14 2007	Sahara Rocks!!!!	Myself and Fiance have just returned from a weeks holiday in Las Vegas. We were so un-decided before we went as to which hotel to stay in and finally decided on the Sahara. We wanted a not to expensive hotel but in a decent location on the strip. We were a little unsure what we were going to arrive to having read some of the reviews. Upon arriving we were pleasantly suprised! The hotel yes a little dated but who cares. The staff were extremely friendly and always willing to help. We booked a Deluxe room and was given a room with a view of the strip, pool and hills. FAB VIEW! The room very spacious and very clean. Yes a few marks on the carpet but nothing that would make me give this hotel a bad review. The bed was the best kingsize we have ever slept in. The bathroom was very clean and towels changed everyday. They provide safes at reception free of charge which was great. The Caravan Cafe was amazing. This is in the hotel just through the casino and we had breakfast there every day as it is great value and the staff again are so friendly and polite. We also ate in the Mexican which was ace! There is a lot of building work going on at the sahara end of the strip but I promise you you cant hear any noise and it really didn't interfere with us. Infact we found it all really interest to see the developments.The monorail was a godsend. It is only £4.50 each for a day pass. You can ride it as many times a day. We couldn't have survived without it. The hotel isn't too far out from the rest of the strip. It looks like it is on the map but it is only a 10 minute walk to say the Venitian or Fashion Show Mall. (And that was with 3 inch heels on!!!) The pool and pool area was clean and tidy with plenty of loungers to go around. We would defo stay at the Sahara again without a doubt and were sad to read the bad reviews people had logged as we nearly didn't stay at the Sahara due to them. We are glad we took a chance as our holiday was made perfect due to the SAHARA's staff, location and cleanliness!!! See you again soon SAHARA x z &amp; a	
Oct 10 2007 	Great Holiday	Our second time at the Sahara - it suits our budget while still being on the strip.The rooms are dated and in need of repair but if like us you don't intend on spending you holiday in your room the who cares... the beds are comfortable and that's what really matters.The monorail is more expensive that in used to be but it is probably still cheaper to do that than stay in a south strip hotel.Beer prices have gone up since last year too but it's only a short walk to the slots of fun ;-)Having said that, this time was a holiday of drinking and gambling and I have to say I enjoyed my stay at the Sahara. I've stayed south strip and it is nice not to have to walk for 20 mins just to get out of the hotel. Everything here is close by. Even the rest of the strip if you don't mind a walk and it's not too hot.I had some great nights/mornings in the Sahara playing penny slots and drinking. Some of the cocktail waitresses were great, you didn't even have to ask for another drink they just brought you one.I also had quite a bit of luck luck there on the slots this time too ;-)There is a bus stop right outside if you fancy a trip downtown which is always worth a visit.Since you are at the end of the monorail it's easy to get to the rest of the strip if you don't fancy the walk (although you can get a taxi easy enough if you want if). The monorail can work out expensive so work out in advance how often you intend to use it and buy the right ticket. There were some good coupons avalable in the many free magazines so take advantage of them.By far the best moment of the holiday is not a typical one. A LV resident we had met a few days before offered to take us out for the day into the LV mountains. She had already told us some great tales of the way the old LV used to be and that in itself made this trip special. But back to the mountains.We couldn't wait. This meant off roading up the mountains!! We got so far up and stopped to take it all in. It was so quiet and peacefull up there.We took a wrong turn and the terrain got rough!!. Luckily she had experience of off roading and got us through although her car took a battering; I couldn't believe the size of the rocks and ravines she had to navigate through - say what you like about women drivers, I'm sure glad she was in charge.We got back on track and on into the mountains.. fantastic scenery so far and a great experience. Then we came across some wild horses. She had brought some apples etc in case we saw them. They looked like they needed them too - skinny animals but great to see horses in the wild.Given the terrain she decided to take us on through the mountains rather than go back. We went on to the next town. This was great for me as we were seeing more of Nevada than I ever hoped.We went for lunch in the next town before driving the long way back to LV. We stopped off at an old saloon which has been there for about 100 years or so. Tiny place, world famous among bikers. I think we were all glad of a drink, covered in desert sand and dirt - a badge of honour for our mountain trip and we didn't care one bit.This was our last day and by far the most memorable. I won't mention her name but if she is reading this then you made that holiday a special one!!!! I hope we see you again.	
