Oct 7 2007 	A-OK for an affordable place to stay.	After some of the negative reviews I have read on here since my return I almost felt compelled to write a review in defence of The Sahara. My wife and I stayed here a week ago, it was my 6th trip to Vegas and her second. Since neither of us was new to the Vegas experience we figured we'd try to save a few bucks and found the best deal online at the Sahara's website. We also picked it for easy access to the Monorail and for a bit of old Vegas nostalgia. Based on info from other reviews on this site I made sure to select a &quot;Deluxe&quot; room in the Tangiers Tower. The rate at the time was $60 a night after all taxes and fees, or at least half the price of many other mid to lower end properties on the strip. The room as mentioned in other reviews was about a Comfort Inn quality and was clean with no problems or strange smells. For the money we were paying I was more than happy with the room as was my wife. We had booked and received a non-smoking King room facing Las Vegas Blvd. All hotel staff we encountered were polite and efficient.We ate at the Buffet twice and the NASCAR Cafe and Caravan Cafe once each. All dining experiences were great for the money, good quality and cleanliness all around and with friendly service.The casino was almost ideal for our needs, big enough to have good variety but not so large you couldn't find your way around. The only negative for us was that later in the evening the ventalation system didnt seem able to keep up with the smoke, but in Vegas this can happen in a lot of casinos.Yes the Sahara is on the north end and kind of in the middle of nowhere due to the re-development going on around it. But with the monorail being so easy to access it was no trouble at all to tour the whole strip with a short ride.We didn't use the pool, but the area looked nice and clean and the other guests I spoke to while we were there who had used the pool had nothing but positive things to say.There were timeshare reps in a few locations in the hotel lobby and near the NASCAR Cafe, but the timeshare people seem to be everywhere in Vegas no matter what hotel you are walking through, so I can't fault the Sahara for that. (Just say &quot;No thank you.&quot; and they'll leave you alone, it's not hard to do. :-)All in all we were very happy with the Sahara and would not hesitate to stay there again.	
