Sep 1 2007 	No problems AT ALL!	Vegas baby!We came to stay at the sahara late August this year, infact whilst writing this we just moved on from there to LA. Here's our stay in a few short paragraphs.We arrived late, about midnight, after riding a 14hr greyhound bus from San Francisco. We've stayed in a combination of Hostels, motels and hotels during this particular trip, so have had a pretty broad appreciation of accomodation. We've also visited Vegas before, staying at an equally styled hotel to the Sahara (stardust, sadly now blown to smitherines else we'd have stayed there again). Check-in was fine, the queue was a few people long, but there were several staff working at the time. The check-in guy was polite and friendly, and we picked up some mail that had been waiting for us without a problem. Now then, people seem to be complaining about the rooms. I'll state this now, we stayed in the NEW tower (tangiers tower) built in 1991. This should help avoid any confusion. After checking in, we headed to the room. There seems to be a thing about vomit in elevators, and guess what? There was! but to be honest, it's vegas... you'd be pretty damn lucky to go somwhere that's free from either vomit or porn, or a combination of the two.Large room, clean clean clean. Good TV channels, wireless keyboard (so you can access the net through the TV... I think). One thing I don't agree with about this hotel, but it's the same for most places in vegas, is the wireless internet charge of $11.99 a day. We decided to get it for two days, and it was a good strong connection but still pretty pricey. The AC in the room was good, not icey like I prefer, but still, no night sweats (even after several margaritas!).The buffett is great for the price, we hit the 'best buffett in vegas' at planet hollywood one night, which at double the cost of Sahara was doubley amazing. However, for a decent meal with basic food, great roasts and free sodas, the Sahara was cool. We spent a great 5 nights here for a minimal amount of money (we paid the same here for a grotty tiny room at a hostel in new york, trust me, Sahara was 10000% better than that), and we would definitely return here (perhaps requesting tangiers tower...).Positives about the hotel:+ The monorail, great connections to the lower strip, if a little pricey at $5 a trip of $9(when on a special rate) a day (usually $15). Runs till 2/3am+ The pool, not as elaborate at some vegas pools, but hey, you're not paying for the bellagio or the venetion, so why expect their facilities?+ Speed the ride, this is ACE, and not as rough as the new york new york 'coaster.+ Not a massive casino floor, you won't get lost! there's everything there though, slots and tables, pretty good for an amature gambler.+ Good room service prices .+ TV checkout, much quicker than waiting in line!Negatives:- Pretty north of the strip, but you pay the same price here as for the Stratosphere which is about 3 blocks further north!Just remember guys, this ISNT the bellagio or any of the high class casinos and shouldn't be compared against them when you look at the price difference, it's an oldie but a goodie!	
